===Etymology===
First attested in 1624; from the {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|πολυμαθής||tr=polumathēs|having learnt much|lang=grc}}, from {{term|sc=polytonic|πολύς||tr=polus|much|lang=grc}} + {{term|sc=polytonic|μάθη|lang=grc}} (''mathē'', “learning”; from {{term|sc=polytonic|μανθάνω|lang=grc}}, ''manthanō'' “I learn”); compare {{term|opsimath|lang=en}}, {{term|philomath|lang=en}}, {{term|polyhistor|lang=en}}, {{term|polymathic|lang=en}}, {{term|polymathist|lang=en}}, and {{term|polymathy|lang=en}}, as well as the {{etyl|fr|-}} {{term|polymathe|lang=fr}}.

